Libraries
```{r}
library(dplyr) # for data manipulation
library(ggplot2) # for histogram
```

# Load in Data
```{r}
all_sars <- readRDS("~/Desktop/Dartmouth/6. Fall 2023 Term/QBS 181 Data Wrangling/5. Final Project/cleandata.rds")
subset_sars <- readRDS("~/Desktop/Dartmouth/6. Fall 2023 Term/QBS 181 Data Wrangling/5. Final Project/cleandata2.rds")

demos <- read.csv("~/Desktop/Dartmouth/6. Fall 2023 Term/QBS 181 Data Wrangling/5. Final Project/summary_data_clean.csv")
pop <- readRDS("~/Desktop/Dartmouth/6. Fall 2023 Term/QBS 181 Data Wrangling/5. Final Project/pop.rds")
```

Create table of only last entry (with maximum cumulative cases) per country with greater than max cumulative cases
```{r}
max_all_sars <- all_sars %>% group_by(Country) %>% summarise_all(last)
print(max_all_sars)
```

Basic histogram of cases
```{r}
hist(max_all_sars$Cases, breaks = 100)
```

Pretty Histogram of cases
```{r}
# used Coolors to find nice colors to match presentation

p <- ggplot(data = max_all_sars, aes(x = Cases)) +
  geom_histogram(fill = "#219EBC", color = "#023047", bins = 100) +
  labs(title = "Histogram of Cumulative Cases", x = "Max. Number of Cumulative Cases", y = "Frequency")
     
p + theme_minimal()
```

Count total number of countries with less than 10 cumulative cases (used chatGPT to find nrow() function)
```{r}
max_all_sars %>% filter(Cases < 10) %>% nrow() # 28, out of 37 countries = 75.7% of countries in dataset
```
